result.execSummary:
The defendant Kayle J. LaRose was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Trespass [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.14(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

(2:00 PM cases 22CF311, 22CF386 called.) All parties and court personnel appear via Zoom. 
Defendant Kayle J. LaRose appeared by video, in custody in Taycheedah Correctional Institution. Attorney George E. Miller in court for Kayle J. LaRose. Prosecuting attorney Kelly Ronquist in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
State in compliance with victim notification requirements. Agreement has been reached and is recited by counsel.
Defendant waives right to a personal appearance and wants to proceed. Court accepts the defendant's waiver to a personal appearance.
Defendant pleads No Contest to 22CF311 Count 3: Obstructing an Officer as Repeater and 22CF386 Count 2: Criminal Trespass as Repeater. Prior offenses acknowledged for repeater enhancers.
Defendant is advised of charges, maximum penalties, elements of the crime(s) and constitutional rights. 
Court accepts the defendant's No Contest pleas and finds the defendant Guilty of 22CF311 Count 3 and 22CF386 Count 2.

Court withholds sentence and places the defendant on probation for 24 months with the following conditions:
90 days jail with Huber privileges or Electronic Monitoring if the jail determines eligible, stayed pending further order of the Court on 22CF311 Count 3 and 22CF386 Count 2 concurrent. Any conditions, programming or treatment per the agent and follow through with recommendations. Provide DNA sample and pay surcharge and pay court costs. 5 days credit on case 22CF311 and 4 days credit on case 22CF386 if probation revoked. Any remaining charges are dismissed and read in.
